text: Does anyone know what the TV ad is all about?

Isn't that only the case if the actor wants it to be 'right' that they can essentially update it?

Lets compare ChatGPT and ChatDKG. Say there is a ton of data being uploaded on DKG, along with tons of misinformation/false statements. Is there anything preventing ChatDKG from acting like GPT in that it can give false information? I believe DKG always has sources you can verify, but I think in practice it would be like wikipedia where everyone assumes what is written is true.

How do you know anything is correct? DKG is not about filtering the content or deciding what is correct or what is not, it's about creating a single repository with knowledge, where surely you will find both truthful and falseful statements, but there are few things to consider:

1. Falseful statements or misinformation is expensive to produce
2. You can have bunch of sources, which you can always compare
3. It's you who decides what is more likely to be true for you, same way as anything else in the World. DKG is a tool that makes finding your truth easier via structuring and gathering knowledge in one place
Thank you for the clarification. The costs of a potential massive misinformation upload I had in my mind isn't something I considered.

just as an example, right now if you open media they will tell you that 96% of all studies have confirmed that there is climate change and the science is settled. What they don't tell is that all these 96% were paid to be produced, and if your results didn't confirm climate change, you don't get payment. Now you are screwed, there is no easy way to make up your mind. BUT with the DKG, you can filter out all the papers that were paid by that certain foundation and you will see the independent ones, produced by scientists for the science and not because they will be paid

Example with ChatGPT: How do you know that something ChatGPT generates isn't correct? You probably google it (checking different sources). How do you know Google gives you the correct information? There is no way to tell its correct, you just trust that their algorithm is good enough to give you the most likely to be true information on top of the page
Same way it works with the DKG, just that everything is in one massive structure

Thank you for the clarification. The costs of a potential massive misinformation upload I had in my mind isn't something I considered.

And all information requires using a limited supply token that exists across multiple chains and is increasingly getting more and more scarce

you can easily do that as each study must say if they received money or not and from whom. With the DKG, you just filter out that one entity that subsidized those 96% and then you get results to make your own decision
